aa(lp181
VHow do we construct something like this?
p182
aVWell, I'll quickly show you two options.
p183
aVThe first is to create a kind of balloon structure,
p184
aVfill it with bacteria, then allow the sand to wash over the balloon,
p185
aVpop the balloon, as it were, disseminating the bacteria into the sand and solidifying it.
p186
aVThen, a few years afterwards,
p187
aVusing permacultural strategies,
p188
aVwe green that part of the desert.
p189
aa(lp190
VThe second alternative would be to use injection piles.
p191
aVSo, we pushed the piles down through the dune,
p192
aVand we create an initial bacterial surface.
p193
aVWe then pull the piles up through the dune
p194
aVand we're able to create almost any conceivable shape inside of the sand
p195
aVwith the sand acting as a mold as we go up.
p196
aVSo, we have a way of turning sand into sandstone,
p197
aVand then creating these habitable spaces inside of the desert dunes.
p198
aa(lp199
VBut, what should they look like?
p200
aVWell, I was inspired, for my architectural form, by tafoni,
p201
aVwhich look a little bit like this, this is a model representation of it.
p202
aVThese are cavernous rock structures that I found on the site in Sokoto.
p203
aVAnd I realized that if I scaled them up, they would provide me
p204
aVwith good spatial qualities,
p205
aVfor ventilation, for thermal comfort, and for other things.
p206
aVNow, part of the formal control over this structure
p207
aVwould be lost to nature, obviously,
p208
aVas the bacteria do their work.
p209
aVAnd I think this creates a kind of boundless beauty actually.
p210
aVI think there is really something in that articulation
p211
aVthat is quite nice.
p212
aVWe see the result, the traces, if you like,
p213
aVof the Bacillus pasteurii being harnessed to sculpt the desert
p214
aVinto these habitable environments.
